to the editor re on africa 's fluid borders my land is your land news article april 16 articles about africa often endorse the view that the continent 's political and economic troubles stem from the absurd borders constructed by the european colonial powers which are said to unnaturally divide and lump together ethnic groups but it is not clear how any set of interstate borders could have naturally divided up sub saharan africa in the late 19th century what today appear as well defined and politically mobilized ethnic groups in africa often had at the time of conquest no sense of common ethnicity or political interest it is more a case of political boundaries leading to the development of ethnic groups than political boundaries dividing up and lumping together pre existing natural groups colonial boundaries shaped the way that african intellectuals put together political coalitions in challenging colonial domination james d fearon stanford calif april 18 2000 the writer is an associate professor of political science at stanford

